#!/usr/bin/env perl
use utf8;
use v5.42;
use Mojolicious::Lite -signatures;
use Time::Str qw(str2time time2str);
use Time::Str::TimeZone qw(timezone);

my %IANA_TO_ZONE;

get '/' => sub ($c) {
	my $hash = timezones( map { $c->param($_) } qw(lat lon date) );
	my $status = exists $hash->{'errors'} ? 400 : 200;

	$hash->{'version'} = '1.1';
	$hash->{'url'} = $c->req->url;

	$c->render(
		json   => $hash,
		status => $status,
		);
	};

app->start;  # this statement needs to be last

=encoding utf8

=head1 NAME

geo-timezone - add a timezone to a datetime based on geo-coordinates

=head1 SYNOPSIS

Run the server:

	% perl geo-timezone

Access the API:

	% curl http://127.0.0.1:3000?date=2026-03-04+01:56;lat=44.00;lon=-83.789

=head1 DESCRIPTION

I have a project that has local times and geocoordinates, but no timezone
information. This makes certain date operations problematic. This little API
takes a local date and geocoordinates and figures out the IANA timezone and
the offset.

I barely did anything. All the hard work was already done by the
[Geo::Location::TimeZoneFinder](https://metacpan.org/pod/Geo::Location::TimeZoneFinder)
Perl module and the
[evansiroky/timezone-boundary-builder)](https://github.com/evansiroky/timezone-boundary-builder)
project. I just wrapped a Mojolicious Lite app around it so my other tasks can query it.

The decisions are all based on my particular problem. If they don't work for you,
it's easy enough to change the response.

=head2 Requests

There's one endpoint, which has no name. It's just the root path:

	% curl "http://127.0.0.1:3000/?date=2026-03-04+01:56&lat=44.00&lon=-83.789"

Mojolicious does not support semicolon parameter separators, so you must
use the `&` separator, which means that a command-line call needs to quote
the URL, or go the long way with C<curl>:

	% curl -G \
		--data-urlencode lat=-83.789 \
		--data-urlencode lon=44.134 \
		--data-urlencode "date=2026-03-04 01:56" \
		http://127.0.0.1:3000

The query takes three parameters:

=over 4

=item * lat - latitude in decimal

=item * lon - longitude in decimal

=item * date - as `YYYY-MM-DD HH::MM`

=back

=head2 Errors

If the date or the geo-coordinates are bad, the response returns a 400 error
(Bad Request) and a JSON object with an C<errors> array with the error messages.

Here's a longitude with a magnitude over 180:

	% curl -s -v "http://127.0.0.1:3000?date=2026-03-04+01:56&lat=44.00&lon=-283.789"
	*   Trying 127.0.0.1:3000...
	* Connected to 127.0.0.1 (127.0.0.1) port 3000
